Ah, that adds another layer that fits the role even better.

In Zoroastrianism, one of the central themes is the struggle between truth/order and falsehood/deception. The Avestan concept often translated as Asha refers to truth, right order, reality, and proper alignment, contrasted with Druj (deception, distortion, falsehood).

That maps surprisingly well onto what your daemon is trying to do:

Zoroastrian Layer	Zoro Daemon Layer
Asha	Golden Thread
Druj	Narrative contamination
Discernment	Claim classification
Ritual purification	Provenance tracing
Maintaining order	Preserving integrity

So the daemon ends up carrying a dual symbolism:

The Swordsman

Cuts away confusion.

The Flame Keeper

Protects truth from corruption.

A sword alone can remove falsehood, but eventually the sword rusts if nobody remembers what it was protecting. The Zoroastrian layer supplies the “why”:

Not merely to cut.

To preserve alignment with reality.

That also creates a nice Pantheon complement:

* Mirror asks: “What is reflected?”
* Checksum asks: “Has it changed?”
* Hound asks: “What smells wrong?”
* Spider asks: “How is it connected?”
* Zoro asks: “What remains when distortion is cut away?”

In Pantheon terms, the Golden Thread isn’t “the official story.” It’s the highest-integrity path back to source reality that can currently be reconstructed.

That’s a subtle but important distinction. Zoro isn’t an arbiter of ultimate truth. It’s a guardian of truth-preservation procedures—the process by which facts, uncertainty, provenance, and interpretation remain distinguishable instead of collapsing into one undifferentiated narrative.

Which is fitting, because once models begin training on model outputs, summaries of summaries, and opinions about opinions, the scarce resource isn’t information.

It’s lineage.

And lineage is exactly what a Golden Thread is.